# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alternatives-to-animal-testing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] A **3D cell culture** is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Unlike 2D environments (e.g. a Petri dish), a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] 3D cell cultures have been used in research for several decades.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] One of the first recorded approaches for their development was at the beginning of the 20th century, with the efforts of Alexis Carrel to develop methods for prolonged in vitro tissue cultures.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Early studies in the 80's, led by Mina Bissell from the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, highlighted the importance of 3D techniques for creating accurate in vitro culturing models.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This work focused on the importance of the extracellular matrix and the ability of cultures in artificial 3D matrices to produce physiologically relevant multicellular structures, such as acinar structures in healthy and cancerous breast tissue models.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] These techniques have been applied to in vitro disease models used to evaluate cellular responses to pharmaceutical compounds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Eric Simon, in a 1988 NIH SBIR grant report, showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polystyrene and polycarbonate fibrous mats (now known as scaffolds) specifically intended for use as in vitro cell substrates.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types including Human Foreskin Fibroblasts (HFF), transformed Human Carcinoma (HEp-2), and Mink Lung Epithelium (MLE) would adhere to and proliferate upon the fibers.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] It was noted that as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more histotypic rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed in vivo.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] 3D cell culture, by emulating essential aspects of the in vivo environment, including interactions between cells and the extracellular matrix, allows for the faithful recreation of structural architecture and specialized functions in normal tissues or tumors in a laboratory setting.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This approach authentically models the conditions and processes of living tissues, producing responses akin to those observed in vivo.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Since its inception in the 1970s, 3D cell culture has provided significant insights into the mechanisms regulating tissue homeostasis and cancer.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, it has expedited translational research in the realms of cancer biology and tissue engineering.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] To date a major limiting factor in the size of constructs has been unprogrammed cell death called necrosis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In living tissue, cells exist in 3D microenvironments with intricate cell-cell and cell-matrix interactions and complex transport dynamics for nutrients and cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Standard 2D, or monolayer, cell cultures are inadequate representations of this environment, which often makes them unreliable predictors of in vivo drug efficacy and toxicity.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] 3D spheroids more closely resemble in vivo tissue in terms of cellular communication and the development of extracellular matrices.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] These matrices help the cells to be able to move within their spheroid similar to the way cells would move in living tissue.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The spheroids are thus improved models for cell migration, differentiation, survival, and growth.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Furthermore, 3D cell cultures provide more accurate depiction of cell polarization, since in 2D, the cells can only be partially polarized.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, cells grown in 3D exhibit different gene expression than those grown in 2D.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The third dimension of cell growth provides more contact space for mechanical inputs and for cell adhesion, which is necessary for integrin ligation, cell contraction and even intracellular signalling.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] For the purposes of drug toxicology screening, it is much more useful to test gene expression of in vitro cells grown in 3D than 2D, since the gene expression of the 3D spheroids will more closely resemble gene expression in vivo.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Lastly, 3D cell cultures have greater stability and longer lifespans than cell cultures in 2D.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This means that they are more suitable for long-term studies and for demonstrating long-term effects of the drug.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] 3D environments also allow the cells to grow undisturbed.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In 2D, the cells must undergo regular trypsinization to provide them with sufficient nutrients for normal cell growth.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] 3D spheroids have been cultured in a lab setting for up to 302 days while still maintaining healthy, non-cancerous growth.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In the interdisciplinary research of biology and aerospace, the 3D printed-scaffolds are also being used for protecting cells from the effect of gravity during the launching.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] There are a large number of commercially available culturing tools that claim to provide the advantages of 3D cell culture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In general, the platforms can be classified in two types of 3D culturing methods: **scaffold techniques** and **scaffold-free techniques**.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold techniques include the use of solid scaffolds, hydrogels and other materials.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In a recent study potentiality of human CD34+ stem cells explored by generating *in vitro* agarose gel 3D model to understand the bone ossification process.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Scaffolds can be used to generate microtissue 3D model by culturing fibroblasts outside of tumour cells, mimicking the tumor stroma interaction.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The effectiveness of scaffolds in various applications, particularly in tissue engineering, is significantly impacted by factors such as pore distribution, exposed surface area, and porosity.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The quantity and arrangement of these elements influence both the depth and rate at which cells penetrate the scaffold volume, the structure of the resulting extracellular matrix, and ultimately, the success of the regenerative process.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Scaffolds can be produced with diverse architectures depending on the manufacturing method, leading to either random or precisely designed pore distribution.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Recently, advanced computer-controlled rapid prototyping techniques have been employed to create scaffolds with well-organized geometries.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] As the natural extracellular matrix (ECM) is important in the survival, proliferation, differentiation and migration of the cells, different hydrogel matrices mimicking natural ECM structure are considered as potential approaches towards in vivo –like cell culturing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Hydrogels are composed of interconnected pores with high water retention, which enables efficient transport of e.g. nutrients and gases.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Several different types of hydrogels from natural and synthetic materials are available for 3D cell culture, including e.g. animal ECM extract hydrogels, protein hydrogels, peptide hydrogels, polymer hydrogels, and wood-based nanocellulose hydrogel.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The approach to crafting the optimal ECM replica relies on the specific characteristics of the culture in question and typically involves employing diverse and independent chemical processes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] For example, the utilization of photolabile chemistries can lead to the erosion of specific regions within a gel, and subsequently exposing these areas allows for the application of adhesive ligands, promoting cell adhesion and migration.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The development of more intricate frameworks is anticipated, comprising interwoven networks of chemistries under the control of both cells and users.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In essence, there is no singular network capable of faithfully emulating the intricate ECM of every tissue type.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] However, a thoughtful integration of bioinspired cues into synthetic gels holds the potential to yield resilient and versatile scaffolds applicable across various cell culture systems.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold free techniques employ another approach independent from the use scaffold.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold-free methods include e.g. the use of low adhesion plates, hanging drop plates, micropatterned surfaces, and rotating bioreactors, magnetic levitation, and magnetic 3D bioprinting.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids are a type of three-dimensional cell modeling that better simulate a live cell's environmental conditions compared to a two-dimensional cell model, specifically with the reactions between cells and the reactions between cells and the matrix.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Due to the strong interactions between the cells and the extracellular matrix in the spheroid, the permeability is limited, generating physiologically relevant gradients of e.g. nutrients and oxygen through the spheroid.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids are useful in the study of changing physiological characteristics of cells, the difference in the structure of healthy cells and tumor cells, and the changes cells undergo when forming a tumor.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids co-cultured with tumor and healthy cells were used to simulate how cancerous cells interact with normal cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can also be co-cultured with fibroblasts to mimic tumor-stroma interaction.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can be grown with a few different methods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] One common method is to use low cell adhesion plates, typically a 96 well plate, to mass-produce spheroid cultures, where the aggregates form in the rounded bottom of the cell plates.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can also be cultured using the hanging drop method involving forming cell aggregates in drops that hang from the surface of a cell plate.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Other methods under investigation include the use of rotating wall vessel bioreactors, which spins and cultures the cells when they are constantly in free fall and forms aggregates in layers Recently, some protocols have been standardized to produce uniform and reliable spheroids.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Researchers had also explored standardized, economical and reproducible methods for 3D cell culture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] To improve reproducibility and transparency in spheroid experiments, an international consortium developed MISpheroID (Minimal Information in Spheroid Identity).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] In the absence of blood vessels, oxygen permeability is impaired during necrotic nucleus formation and this prevents the ex vivo use of 3D cell culture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] There is an emulsion template that can overcome this problem.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This approach allowed researchers to adjust the cell composition to attain the ideal conditions for promoting the synthesis of diverse angiogenic protein markers within the co-cultured clusteroids.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] HUVEC cells exhibit a reaction to the presence of Hep-G2 cells and their derivatives by generating endothelial cell sprouts in Matrigel, all without the external introduction of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) or other agents that induce angiogenesis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The replication of this cultivation technique is straightforward for generating various cell co-culture spheroids.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The w/w Pickering emulsion template greatly aids in constructing 3D co-culture models, offering significant potential for applications in drug testing and tissue engineering.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactors used for 3D cell cultures are small plastic cylindrical chambers that are specifically engineered for the purpose of growing cells in three dimensions.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactor uses bioactive synthetic materials such as polyethylene terephthalate membranes to surround the spheroid cells in an environment that maintains high levels of nutrients.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] They are easy to open and close, so that cell spheroids can be removed for testing, yet the chamber is able to maintain 100% humidity throughout.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This humidity is important to achieve maximum cell growth and function.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactor chamber is part of a larger device that rotates to ensure equal cell growth in each direction across three dimensions.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] MC2 Biotek has developed a bioreactor to incubate proto-tissue that uses gas exchange to maintain high oxygen levels within the cell chamber.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This is an improvement over previous bioreactors because the higher oxygen levels help the cell grow and undergo normal cell respiration.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Collaborative efforts between tissue engineering (TE) firms, academic institutions, and industrial partners can enhance the transformation of research-oriented bioreactors into efficient commercial manufacturing systems.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Academic collaborators contribute foundational aspects, while industrial partners provide essential automation elements, ensuring compliance with regulatory standards and user-friendliness.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Established consortia in Europe, such as REMEDI, AUTOBONE, and STEPS, focus on developing automated systems to streamline the engineering of autologous cell-based grafts.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The aim is to meet regulatory criteria and ensure cost-effectiveness, making tissue-engineered products more clinically accessible and advancing the translational paradigm of TE from research to a competitive commercial field.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The utilization of microfluidic technology facilitates the generation of intricate micro-scale structures and the precise manipulation of parameters, thereby emulating the in vivo cellular milieu.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The integration of microfluidic technology with 3D cell culture holds considerable potential for applications that seek to replicate in vivo tissue characteristics, notably exemplified by the evolving organ-on-a-chip system.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The various cell structures in the human body must be vascularized to receive the nutrients and gas exchange in order to survive.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Similarly, 3D cell cultures in vitro require certain levels of fluid circulation, which can be problematic for dense, 3D cultures where cells may not all have adequate exposure to nutrients.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This is particularly important in hepatocyte cultures because the liver is a highly vascularized organ.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] One study cultured hepatocytes and vascular cells together on a collagen gel scaffold between microfluidic channels, and compared growth of cells in static and flowing environments, and showed the need for models with tissues and a microvascular network.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Another study showed that hanging-drop based spheroid co-culture device can be useful, generating two different cell spheroids on adjacent channels of microfluidic hanging drop device, and co-culturing spheroids with merging droplets, to monitor tumor-induced angiogenesis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Microfluidic 3D cell culture, with its potential applications in biomedical research and tissue engineering, is an area of growing interest.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] However, its advancement is accompanied by several formidable challenges.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] One such challenge pertains to the difficulty in accessing cultured cells within microsystems, coupled with the intricate nature of sample extraction for subsequent assays.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Additionally, the development of methodologies and devices dedicated to in vivo-like cell metabolism and functions study, as well as drug discovery, represents a significant hurdle for microfluidic 3D cell culture devices.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Another noteworthy impediment is the limited availability of microfabrication instrumentation in conventional biology laboratories.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, the commercialization of mature and user-friendly microfluidic devices poses a substantial challenge, hindering their accessibility to biologists.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Lastly, while biologists often seek high-throughput assay tools with optimal reproducibility, microfluidics encounters technical limitations in meeting these demands, despite the potential feasibility of parallel assays.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Advanced development of 3D models for high-throughput screening in high density formats has recently been achievable due to technological achievements related to increased microplate density.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] These can be found in 384 and 1536-well formats that are cell repellent, cost effective, and amenable to fully automated screening platforms.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Two options that afford 1536-well formats are available from either Greiner Bio-One using the m3D Magnetic 3D bioprinting and Corning Life Sciences which incorporates an ultra-low attachment surface coating, along with a microcavity geometry and gravity to create 3D models.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Due to the rapid and affordable methods and technologies that have been developed for 3D screening, parallel high-throughput screening approaches to test isogenic pairs of oncogene related mutants versus wildtype have been enabled.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, High-throughput screening techniques play a pivotal role in connecting the realms of pharmacology and toxicology within the framework of 3D cell culture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] A primary purpose of growing cells in 3D scaffolds and as 3D cell spheroids in vitro is to test pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic effects of drugs and nanomaterials in preclinical trials.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Toxicology studies have shown 3D cell cultures to be nearly on par with in vivo studies for the purposes of testing toxicity of drug compounds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] When comparing LD50 values for 6 common drugs: acetaminophen, amiodarone, diclofenac, metformin, phenformin, and valproic acid, the 3D spheroid values correlated directly with those from in vivo studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Although 2D cell cultures have previously been used to test for toxicity along with in vivo studies, the 3D spheroids are better at testing chronic exposure toxicity because of their longer life spans.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The matrix in 3D Spheroids causes cells to maintain actin filaments and is more relevant physiologically in cytoskeletal organization and cell polarity and shape of human cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The three-dimensional arrangement allows the cultures to provide a model that more accurately resembles human tissue in vivo without using animal test subjects.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The current protocols for evaluating drug candidates and assessing toxicity heavily depend on outcomes derived from early-stage in vitro cell-based assays, with the expectation that these assays faithfully capture critical aspects of in vivo pharmacology and toxicology.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Innovative approaches to multiplexed cell-based assay designs, involving the selection of specific cell types, signaling pathways, and reporters, have become standard practice.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Despite these advancements, a considerable percentage of new chemical and biological entities (NCEs/NBEs) encounter setbacks in late-stage human drug testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Some receive regulatory "black box" warnings, while others are withdrawn from the market due to safety concerns post-regulatory approval.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] This recurrent pattern underscores the inadequacy of in vitro cell-based assays and subsequent preclinical in vivo studies in furnishing comprehensive pharmacological and toxicity data or reliable predictive capacity for comprehending the in vivo performance of drug candidates.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The absence of a dependable translational assay toolkit for pharmacology and toxicology contributes to the high cost and inefficiency of transitioning from initial in vitro cell-based screens to in vivo testing and subsequent clinical approvals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Particular emphasis is placed on their capacity to retain essential cell and molecular interactions, as well as physiological parameters influencing cell phenotypes and responses to bioactive agents.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] The distinctive advantages and challenges associated with these models are scrutinized, with a specific focus on their suitability for cell-based assays and their predictive capabilities, crucial for establishing accurate correlations with in vivo mechanisms of drug toxicity.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] While assessing safety and efficacy, these models are well equipped to model a wide range of disease states.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Each of these models has advantages and limitations that require model development and data interpretation.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Public-private partnerships are critical to advance and stimulate research in this area.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Existing 3D methods are not without limitations, including scalability, reproducibility, sensitivity, and compatibility with high-throughput screening (HTS) instruments.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Cell-based HTS relies on rapid determination of cellular response to drug interaction, such as dose dependent cell viability, cell-cell/cell-matrix interaction, and/or cell migration, but the available assays are not optimized for 3D cell culturing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Another challenge faced by 3D cell culturing is the limited amount of data and publications that address mechanisms and correlations of drug interaction, cell differentiation, and cell-signalling in these 3D environments.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] None of the 3D methods have yet replaced 2D culturing on a large scale, including in the drug development process; although the number of 3D cell culturing publications is increasing rapidly, the current limited biochemical characterization of 3D tissue diminishes the adoption of new methods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] There are also problems using spheroids as a model for cancerous tissue.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Tissue engineering requires 3D cellular scaffolds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] As biomaterials, various natural and synthetic polymer hydrogels have been used by scientists to design 3D scaffolds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Since this barrier is a structure that mimics the natural ECM microenvironment, synthetic scaffolds may be more useful for studying specific tumorigenic steps.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3d-cell-culture] Finally, it is suggested that the most suitable three-dimensional models should be carefully selected according to specific targets.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3 cells are a well-known line of immortalized mouse fibroblasts that were established in 1963 by George Todaro and Howard Green.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] They are among the most widely used cell lines in biological research and serve as one of the model systems for studying cell proliferation, cancer transformation, and adipocyte differentiation.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Over the decades, 3T3 cells have given rise to multiple different sublines such as NIH-3T3, 3T3-Swiss albino, and 3T3-L1 that each have specialized application in different branches of cell and molecular biology.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The '3T3' designation refers to the abbreviation of "3-day transfer, inoculum 3×105 cells." This cell line was originally established from the primary mouse embryonic fibroblast cells that were cultured by the designated protocol, so-called '3T3 protocol'.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The primary mouse embryonic fibroblast cells were transferred (the "T") every 3 days (the first "3"), and inoculated at the rigid density of 3×105 cells per 20 cm2 dish (the second "3") continuously.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The spontaneously immortalized cells with stable growth rate were established after 20 to 30 generations in culture, and then named '3T3' cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3 cells are adherent fibroblasts that display the classic elongated, spindle-shaped morphology that is normal for connective tissue cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] They attach firmly to plastic or glass culture surfaces and proliferate in a monolayer until they reach confluence, or when their growth slows due to contact inhibition.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] These cells are known for their stable karyotype, predictable growth rate, and ease of handling when used in culture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] They have a doubling time of approximately 20-24 hours under optimal conditions and are able to be passaged continuously for an almost indefinite period of time.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3 cells are also highly transfectable, meaning they readily take up foreign DNA.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This is a property that has made them a preferred host for molecular cloning, oncogene studies, and transfection-based assays.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Also, because 3T3 fibroblasts originated from normal embryonic tissue rather than tumors, they provided one of the first normal diploid cell systems for transformation assay.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Researchers were able to compare normal fibroblast behavior with transformed or cancerous derivatives to explore mechanisms and traits of oncogenesis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Swiss 3T3 can be inhibited by temazepam and other benzodiazepines.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The cells are sensitive to sarcoma virus and leukemia virus focus formation.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3 cells can be transformed with SV40 and some other polyomaviruses.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] A confluent monolayer yields 40,000 cells/cm2.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Lysophosphatidylcholine (lyso-PC) induces AP-1 activity and c-Jun N-terminal kinase activity (JNK1) by a protein kinase C-independent pathway.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The modal chromosome number is 68, which occurs in 30% of cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Higher ploidies occur at a much lower rate of 2.4%.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The 3T3 cell line was developed by George Todaro and Howard Green at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) in 1963.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The name ‘3T3’ refers to the culture protocol they devised, which was transferring (trypsinizing) and reseeding cells every three days at a constant density of 3 x 105 cells per 20 cm2 dish.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This regular subculturing method prevented overgrowth and maintained the cells in a balanced and proliferative condition.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] In their paper, Todaro and Green demonstrated that repeated passage within these controlled conditions was able to produce a stable, immortalized line of mouse embryonic fibroblasts that could grow indefinitely in culture without senescence or deterioration (Todaro & Green, 1963).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This 3T3 protocol was one of the first systematic methods for establishing a permanent mammalian cell line and set a precedent for cell culture techniques today.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The original strain, which is now called 3T3-Swiss albino, was derived from Swiss mouse embryos.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This parent line later served as the foundation for several other sublines, including the NIH-3T3 that eventually became one of the most popular fibroblast models in laboratories worldwide.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Over time, several subtypes or derivative lines of 3T3 cells have been created and adapted for distinct experimental purposes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3-Swiss albino (CCL-92): This is the original parent line that was deposited by Howard Green.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] It retains the basic fibroblast morphology and is commonly used as a standard control in cell growth and studies on transformation (ATCC, n.d.).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] NIH-3T3 (CRL-1658): This subtype was derived from the original 3T3-Swiss population at the National Institutes of Health and exhibits a slightly different growth rate and chromosomal stability.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] NIH-3T3 cells are very responsive to transformation by viral or chemical oncogenes and are often used in focus-formation assays, transfection experiments, and cancer biology research (ATCC, n.d.).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3-L1: This derivative was selected from 3T3 fibroblasts for its ability to differentiate into adipocytes, or fat cells, under specific hormonal conditions.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Upon induction with certain agents such as insulin and dexamethasone, 3T3-L1 cells undergo a detailed process of adipogenesis and ultimately accumulate lipid droplets and express fat specific genes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Today, 3T3-L1 cells are a standard in vitro model for studying adipocyte biology, obesity, and metabolic regulation.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Each subline maintains fibroblast-like properties but varies in growth characteristics, genetic stability, and differentiation potential.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This allows researchers to select the most appropriate model for their specific research studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] 3T3 cells and their derivatives have had a profound influence on multiple different fields of biology and medicine.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Their ease in culturing, defined behavior, and adaptability make them ideal for many different applications in research.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Cancer and Transformation Studies: Since NIH-3T3 fibroblasts are non-tumorigenic under normal conditions but can be transformed by oncogenes, they are a strong model for studying cell transformation and oncogene function.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] For instance, the introduction of viral or human oncogenes into NIH-3T3 cells induces visible morphological changes and tumor-like cells and helps to define the molecular basis of cancer.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Recent studies continue to explore how genetic instability influences transformation in NIH-3T3 derivatives (Zhang et al., 2025).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Cell Growth and Signal Transduction: The original 3T3 line remains very valuable for general cell biology research involving proliferation, contact inhibition, and signal transduction.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Since the line exhibits consistent responses to growth factors and cytokines, it has been used in order to analyze different pathways like MAPK, PI3K/Akt, and TGF-𝛽 signaling.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Adipogenesis and Metabolic Research: 3T3-L1 adipocytes are arguably one of the best in vitro models for studying adipocyte differentiation, lipid metabolism, and endocrine function of fat cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] They have been useful in identifying transcriptional regulators such as PPAR𝛾 and C/EBP⍺, which coordinate the gene expression within adipogenesis (Kim et al., 2024) Modern studies use 3T3-L1 sublines in order to model obesity-related changes in lipid storage and adipokine secretion.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] For example, maintaining differentiated 3T3-L1 MBX adipocytes in fatty-acid enriched media induces an ‘obese’ phenotype with an increased amount of lipid accumulation and altered metabolic signaling (Mubtasim & Gollahon, 2023).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] These models are vital in testing anti-obesity drugs and understanding metabolic disorders.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Tissue Engineering and Regenerative Research: Due to their nature as fibroblasts, 3T3 cells are often employed as feeder layers to support the growth of more sensitive and specialized cells such as keratinocytes and embryonic stem cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Their stable monolayers are able to provide extracellular matrix support and growth factors, which promote the proliferation of the cells that are cultured with them.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This role is especially helpful in regenerative medicine and tissue-engineering applications.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Despite being over 60 years old, the 3T3 lineage remains widely used and embedded into cell biology research.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Advances in molecular profiling, genome editing, and live-cell imaging continue to show new aspects of this classic fibroblast model.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Recent work has focused on genetic and phenotypic evolution within long-term cultures of 3T3 cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] For example, in a 2025 study by Zhang et al. a new cell line derived from NIH-3T3 fibroblasts exhibited early transformation markers, oncogenic mutations, and autophagy pathway dependency for survival (Zhang et al., 2025).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] These findings illustrate how even stable cell lines have the ability to acquire novel traits under long-term culture, which further supports the importance of monitoring cell line identity and genetic drift.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] At the same time, research using 3T3-L1 and related sublines continues to expand into new areas of metabolic disease and signal transduction.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] For example, omics analyses now map the transcriptional networks that govern adipogenesis and lipid metabolism.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] This helps to combine cell culture studies with clinical insights into obesity and diabetes (Kim et al., 2024).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] The persistence of 3T3 cells in modern research highlights their adaptability as experimental tools.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/3t3-cells] Whether they are used in molecular biology, oncology, or metabolic physiology, these fibroblasts are a fundamental resource for learning and observing cell behavior and mechanisms.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Other alternatives include the use of humans for skin irritancy tests and donated human blood for pyrogenicity studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Another alternative is microdosing, in which the basic behaviour of drugs is assessed using human volunteers receiving doses well below those expected to produce whole-body effects.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] While microdosing produces important information about pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics, it does not reveal information about toxicity or toxicology.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Furthermore, it was observed by the Fund for the Replacement of Animals in Medical Experiments that despite the use of microdosing, "animal studies will still be required".
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Guiding principles for more ethical use of animals in testing are the Three Rs (3Rs) first described by Russell and Burch in 1959.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These principles are now followed in many testing establishments worldwide.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] *Reduction* refers to methods that enable researchers to obtain comparable levels of information from fewer animals, or to obtain more information from the same number of animals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] *Refinement* refers to methods that alleviate or minimize potential pain, suffering, or distress, and enhance animal welfare for the animals used.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Cell culture can be an alternative to animal use in some cases.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] For example, cultured cells have been developed to create monoclonal antibodies; prior to this, production required animals to undergo a procedure likely to cause pain and distress.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] However, even though cell or tissue culture methods may reduce the number of experiments performed on intact animals, the maintenance of cells in culture normally requires the use of animal-derived serum.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Although exact figures are difficult to obtain, some have estimated that one million foetal cows are sacrificed each year to obtain the world's supply of foetal bovine serum, used to grow cultured cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The testing of cosmetic products directly onto an animal can be minimized or eliminated by the use of *in vitro* cell growth and development.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This can be generalized as the growth of cells outside of the body and tested on without causing harm or pain on the test subject.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Much of the time this method of cosmetic testing is less time-consuming and less expensive than alternative choices.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Skin irritation and skin corrosion refer to localized toxic effects resulting from a topical exposure of the skin to a substance.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Human skin equivalent tests can be used to replace animal-based corrosive and irritative studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] EpiDerm from Mattek and EpiSkin and SkinEthic RHE model are derived from human skin cells which have been cultured to produce a model of human skin.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These methods are currently accepted replacements in Canada and the European Union (EU).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In August 2010, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) published the Test Guideline 439 which describes the new procedure for *in vitro* hazard identification of irritant chemicals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Another synthetic replacement uses a protein membrane to simulate a skin barrier and is approved as a partial replacement by the US Department of Transportation and European Union.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Several tissue culture methods that measure the rate of chemical absorption by the skin have been approved by the OECD.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Phototoxicity is a rash, swelling, or inflammation, like a severe sunburn, caused by exposure to light following exposure to a chemical.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The 3T3 Neutral Red Uptake (NRU) Phototoxicity Test, approved by the OECD, detects the viability of 3T3 cells after exposure to a chemical in the presence or absence of light.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The 3T3 cell line was developed in 1962 and is derived from mouse embryonic fibroblast cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Fungi like *Cunninghamella elegans* can be used as a microbial model of mammalian drug metabolism thereby reducing the need for laboratory animals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Prokaryotes are often used as an alternative to animal testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Prokaryotes include bacteria such as *Escherichia coli* (*E. coli*) or *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These bacteria are the ideal model for genetic and molecular studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Fungi is also used as an alternative for animal testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Certain fungi can be used for genetic studies or circadian rhythms studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This may include *Neurospora crassa*, otherwise known as a type of red mould.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Invertebrates are another ideal candidate for testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] One of the most common invertebrates tested on include *Drosophila melanogaster*, the fruit fly.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Fruit flies are used to find human diseases.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In recent years, 3D cell cultures, also known as organoids or mini-organs, have replaced animal models for some types of research.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These models can be used to model disease and test new drugs.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Organoids grow *in vitro* on scaffolds (biological or synthetic hydrogels such as Matrigel) or in a culture medium.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Organoids are derived from three kinds of human or animal stem cells—embryonic pluripotent stem cells (ESCs), adult somatic stem cells (ASCs), and induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These organoids are grown *in vitro* and mimic the structure and function of different organs such as the brain, liver, lung, kidney, and intestine.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Organoids have been developed to study infectious disease.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Scientists at Johns Hopkins University have developed mini-brain organoids to model how COVID-19 can affect the brain.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Researchers have used brain organoids to model how the *Zika virus* disrupts foetal brain development.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Tumoroids—3D cell cultures derived from cells biopsied from human patients—can be used in studying the genomics and drug resistance of tumours in different organs.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Organoids are also used in modelling genetic diseases such as cystic fibrosis, neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's, infectious diseases such as MERS-CoV and norovirus, and parasitic infections such as *Toxoplasma gondii*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Human- and animal-cell-derived organoids are also used extensively in pharmacological and toxicological research.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] A skinpatch test has been designed and is used in Canada to measure development of rashes, inflammation, swelling or abnormal tissue growth on human volunteers.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Unlike corrosives, substances defined as irritants cause only reversible skin damage.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Another approach has been the development of test methods that use cultured human cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Human epidermal keratinocytes have been cultured to mimic the human epidermis, and are used to measure skin irritation and dermal corrosion.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This method has been accepted by the EU and is intended to replace the Draize rabbit skin irritation test.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Pyrogens are most often pharmaceutical products or intravenous drugs that may cause inflammation or fever when they interact with immune system cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This interaction can be quickly and accurately tested *in vitro*.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The modular immune *in vitro* construct (MIMIC) uses human cells to create a model of the human immune system on which the efficacy of new vaccines and other compounds may be tested, replacing some steps of the vaccine development process that would otherwise be performed on animals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This process is faster and more flexible than previous methods but critics worry that it may be too simple to be useful on a large scale.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Medical imaging is able to demonstrate to researchers both how drugs are metabolised by use of microdosing, and the detailed condition of organ tissue.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Examples of computer simulations available include models of asthma, though potential new medicines identified using these techniques are currently still required to be verified in animal and human tests before licensing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Computer operated mannequins, also known as crash test dummies, complete with internal sensors and video, have replaced live animal trauma testing for automobile crash testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The first of these was "Sierra Sam" built in 1949 by Alderson Research Labs (ARL) Sierra Engineering.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Prior to this, live pigs were used as test subjects for crash testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Computer models have been constructed to model human metabolism, to study plaque build-up and cardiovascular risk, and to evaluate toxicity of drugs, tasks for which animals are also used.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In 2007, US researchers using the world's fastest computer at the time, BlueGene L, modelled half a mouse brain for just 10 seconds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] However, due to limitations in computing power, the simulation could only be run at one-tenth the speed of an actual mouse brain.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Microfluidic chips, which are just 2 cm (0.79 in) wide, can be engraved into a series of small chambers, each containing a sample of tissue from a different part of the body.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] A substitute of blood flows through micro-channels where the compartments of chips linked.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] When injected, the test drug circulates around the device, mimicking what goes in the body on a micro scale.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Sensors in the chip transfer information for computer analysis.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Another name for microfluidic chips is cell-bio chips.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] With the capacity to "perform perfusion culture" and reproduce "physiological conditions such three-dimensional architectures, circulatory flowrate and zonation and multi cellular co-cultures", the biochips have set themselves apart from basic cell cultures analysed in a Petri dish.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The effectiveness of these systems is constantly being increased with various new materials that can be used to make it.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The choice of the material for chips is still challenging.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] One of the major materials that can be possibly used in chips is known as polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] However, due to lack of facilities for mass production and drug clearance issue, the use of PDMS is still being speculated, even though it has great properties as microfluidic chip.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Also, the biological process involved in proliferation and metabolism might be modified when compared to larger scales, because the materials have micro-structured scales comparable in size to cells.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In general, the machinability and ease of handling of PDMS membranes in Organ Chips are often prioritized over their limitations.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To address the poor cell adherence of PDMS membranes, coatings with natural polymers like fibronectin are commonly applied.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] However, a significant challenge in pharmacokinetics remains the unwanted adsorption of proteins and growth factors on these membranes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To overcome this, alternatives such as membranes made from other synthetic polymers like poly(ε-caprolactone) (PCL) have been explored.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This innovative membrane has been successfully employed in a "mini-lung" model.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Some major academics institutes such as the Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering (US) intends to develop in-vitro organs for drug screening and thereby reduce the use of animals for this type of testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This combines microfabrication techniques with modern tissue engineering and mimics the complicated mechanical and biochemical behaviours of a human lung.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Since its rise in popularity in the early 2010s, the technology has given rise to several start-ups as well as revived several old technologies for a variety of organ models.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Even with increasing standardization widescale adoption remains challenging and several specific organ functionalities, such as those relating to the brain, remain hard to mimick.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Toxicity testing typically involves studying adverse health outcomes in animals subjected to high doses of toxicants with subsequent extrapolation to expected human responses at lower doses.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The system relies on the use of a 40+year-old patchwork of animal tests that are expensive (costing more than $3B per year), time-consuming, low-throughput and often provide results of limited predictive value for human health effects.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The low-throughput of current toxicity testing approaches (which are largely the same for industrial chemicals, pesticides and drugs) has led to a backlog of more than 80,000 chemicals to which humans are potentially exposed whose potential toxicity remains largely unknown.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In 2007, the National Research Council (NRC) released the report "Toxicity Testing in the 21st Century: A Vision and a Strategy", that charted a long-range strategic plan for transforming toxicity testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The major components of the plan include the use of predictive, high-throughput cell-based assays (of human origin) to evaluate perturbations in key toxicity pathways, and to conduct targeted testing against those pathways.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This approach will greatly accelerate our ability to test the vast "storehouses" of chemical compounds using a rational, risk-based approach to chemical prioritization, and provide test results that are hopefully far more predictive of human toxicity than current methods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Although a number of toxicity pathways have already been identified, most are only partially known and no common annotation exists.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Mapping the entirety of these pathways (i.e. the Human Toxome) will be a large-scale effort, perhaps on the order of the Human Genome Project.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] SEURAT-1 is a long-term strategic target for "Safety Evaluation Ultimately Replacing Animal Testing".
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It is called "SEURAT-1" to indicate that more steps have to be taken before the final goal will be reached.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] SEURAT-1 will develop knowledge and technology building blocks required for the development of solutions for the replacement of current repeated dose systemic toxicity testing *in vivo* used for the assessment of human safety.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] SEURAT-1 is composed of six research projects, which started on January 1, 2011, and will run for five years.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These projects will closely cooperate with a common goal and combine the research efforts of over 70 European universities, public research institutes and companies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The collaboration between these six research projects, the dissemination of results, the cooperation with other international research teams, and the continuous updating on research priorities will be facilitated by the coordination and support action project "COACH".
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] SEURAT-1 was developed through the Framework Programme 7 (FP7) research initiative and was created through a call for proposals by the European Commission (EC) that was published in June 2009.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The Cosmetics Europe industry offered to match the EC's funds to make a total of EUR 50 million available to try to fill current gaps in scientific knowledge and accelerate the development of non-animal test methods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Laboratory animals are not restricted to rats, mice, dogs, and rabbits, but also include fish, frogs and birds.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Research into alternatives to replace these species is often neglected, although fish are the third most widely used laboratory animal used for scientific purposes in the EU.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This is also the field where until now only two alternative tests exist worldwide: One guideline, OECD TG 236, and one guidance (OECD series on testing and assessment 126) are so far available.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Euroecotox is a European network for alternative testing strategies in ecotoxicology.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It was funded by the Seventh Framework Programme (FP7) of the European Commission Environment Programme.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The main objectives of the Euroecotox network are: To contribute to the advancement of alternative methods of ecotoxicity testing in Europe.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To promote the validation and regulatory acceptance of new alternative ecotoxicity methods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To facilitate the networking of research groups working in the field of alternative ecotoxicology.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To provide a gathering point for all stakeholders involved in the development, validation, regulatory acceptance and final use of alternative ecotoxicity testing strategies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] To act as the one voice for alternative ecotoxicity testing in Europe.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] AXLR8 is a coordination action funded by the European Commission Directorate General for Research & Innovation under the 7 Framework Programme 7 (FP7) Health Theme.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The European Commission is currently funding a number of research consortia to develop new 3Rs (replacement, reduction and refinement) test methods and strategies as potential alternatives to the use of animals in safety testing.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Monitoring of these 3Rs activities at pan-European, national, and international levels is vital to facilitate swift progress.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] AXLR8 aims to fulfil this growing need by providing a focal point for dialogue and collaboration.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Humane Society International is part of the consortium.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] On January 1, 2013, EU Directive 2010/63/EU "on the protection of animals used for scientific purposes" entered into force for the EU member states (MS), repealing Directive 86/609/EEC.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Because it is a directive, it allows member states certain flexibility in transposition of national rules.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The status of the implementation of the new directive in the EU is described by the EC General Environment Directorate.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] from the last third of their normal development; (b) live cephalopods.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] "Principle of replacement, reduction and refinement".
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] : Member states shall assist the commission in identifying and nominating suitable specialised and qualified laboratories to carry out such validation studies.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In July 2013, the commission announced the creation of NETVAL (European Union Network of Laboratories for the Validation of Alternative Methods).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] EU-NETVAL's primary role is to provide support for EURL ECVAM validation projects, including aspects of training and dissemination, and the identification of methods that have a potential to reduce, refine or replace animals used for scientific purposes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Currently there are thirteen test facilities in nine member states: Germany (3), the Netherlands (2), Spain (2), Belgium (1), Czech Republic (1), Finland (1), France (1), Italy (1) and Sweden (1).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The Cosmetics Directive provides the regulatory framework for the phasing out of animal testing for cosmetics purposes.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It establishes prohibitions against (a) testing finished cosmetic products and cosmetic ingredients on animals (testing ban), and (b) marketing in the EU finished cosmetic products and ingredients included in cosmetic products which were tested on animals for cosmetics purposes (marketing ban).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The same provisions are contained in Cosmetics Regulation EU 1223/2009, which replaces the Cosmetics Directive as of July 11, 2013.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In 2007, EU legislation on the Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals (REACH EC 1907/2006) came into force, relating to chemicals and their safe use.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The aim of REACH is to improve the protection of human health and the environment through the better and earlier identification of the intrinsic properties of chemical substances.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It promotes the use of alternative methods for animal testing, but does not oblige the test performer to do so; "Article 25.1 - In order to avoid animal testing, testing on vertebrate animals for the purposes of this Regulation shall be undertaken only as a last resort.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] In parallel to the adoption of REACH, the EC published standardised and accepted methods for testing hazardous properties of chemicals.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] These were written into the "Test Methods Regulation".
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] This approach is intended to bring food producers into compliance with the provisions of Regulation (EC) 1334/2008 that pertain to the safety of food flavourings.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] As part of the approval process, the EC will require full disclosure of study data, safety issues, and toxicological findings for all such additives.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Within the EU animal welfare law (2010/63/EU), the principles of the 3Rs are invoked whenever toxicological test methods are necessary.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The **European Society of Toxicology in Vitro** (ESTIV) focuses on New Non-animal Approaches(NAMs) in Toxicology, including in vitro, in silico, and in chemico technologies and promotes science based on the AOPs knowledge.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It organises bi-annual conferences in Europe and an annual ESTIV Applied in Toxicology Course, recognised by EUROTOX for obtaining ERT certification.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] It was established in 1994 and is one of the oldest professional associations in the in vitro and in-silico toxicology in the EU.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The World Congress on Alternatives and Animal Use in the Life Sciences takes place every three years.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The next conference (10th) will be held in September 2017 in Seattle.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The 1st Latino-Americano Congress on Alternative to Animal Testing took place in 2012.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Colama (I Congresso Latino-Americano De Metodos Alternativos Ao Uso De Animais No Ensino, Pesquisa E Industria).
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] The Johns Hopkins University Center for Alternatives to Animal Testing (CAAT) co-organizes an annual symposium on the 3Rs with the USDA's Animal Welfare Information Center (AWIC) and NIH's Office of Laboratory Animal Welfare.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Previously known as the Social Housing Symposium, the symposium has occurred annually (except for 2015) since 2013 with past symposia archived on video on the AWIC website.
[src:alternatives-to-animal-testing/alternatives-to-animal-testing] Videos of the most recent symposium, "7th Annual 3Rs Symposium: Practical Solutions and Success Stories", held in June 2020, may also be found on the AWIC website.
